internal/storage/memgraph/constitution.go — marshalJSON and unmarshalIfPresent have a sentinel mismatch that creates a subtle inconsistency.

marshalJSON returns "{}" for nil values:
```go
func marshalJSON(v any) (string, error) {
    if v == nil {
        return "{}", nil
    }
    ...
}
```

But when called with a nil slice (e.g., `constitution.Principles` is nil), the Go type system passes a non-nil interface value wrapping a nil slice, so the nil check never fires. json.Marshal(nil_slice) returns "null", not "{}". This means unmarshalIfPresent receives "null" for empty slices, which it correctly skips — but the comment says marshalJSON "Returns '{}' for nil values" which is misleading since most callers pass typed nils that go through json.Marshal.

Suggestion: Drop the special nil branch in marshalJSON (it only matches untyped nil), use json.Marshal directly for all values, and update the sentinel check in unmarshalIfPresent to include "[]" and "null":

```go
func marshalJSON(v any) (string, error) {
    b, err := json.Marshal(v)
    if err != nil {
        return "", fmt.Errorf("marshal json: %w", err)
    }
    return string(b), nil
}

// unmarshalIfPresent: skip "", "{}", "[]", "null"
func unmarshalIfPresent(jsonStr, field string, dest any) error {
    switch jsonStr {
    case "", "{}", "[]", "null":
        return nil
    }
    ...
}
```

This removes misleading special-casing and makes the sentinel logic explicit.

