CLAUDE.md project gotchas explicitly states: 'filepath.Glob does not support recursive ** — only matches one directory level.'

The scanner at internal/scanner/scanner.go uses:
  globs, err := filepath.Glob(filepath.Join(dir, "**", "*.yaml"))

This will NOT recursively search subdirectories for Kubernetes manifests. On Go, filepath.Glob treats '**' as a literal directory name component, not a recursive wildcard. The pattern will only match files in a directory literally named '**', which will be empty in all real cases.

Impact: Kubernetes infrastructure detection is completely non-functional. The TestScan_GoProject test does not cover Kubernetes detection, so this bug passes undetected.

Fix: Use filepath.WalkDir or os.ReadDir recursively instead of filepath.Glob with **. Example:
  filepath.WalkDir(dir, func(path string, d fs.DirEntry, err error) error {
    if err != nil { return nil }
    if strings.HasSuffix(path, ".yaml") { ... }
    return nil
  })

Location: /internal/storage/memgraph/constitution.go does not have this issue; it is in /internal/scanner/scanner.go line ~2494 of the diff.

File: internal/server/constitution_handler.go, line ~7083-7086

In CheckViolation, the handler only checks errors.Is(err, storage.ErrSpecNotFound). When the storage layer has no constitution loaded, memgraph.Store.CheckViolation wraps ErrConstitutionNotFound via fmt.Errorf('memgraph: check violation: %w', storage.ErrConstitutionNotFound). errors.Is would match this wrapped error, but the handler has no branch for ErrConstitutionNotFound, so it falls through to the catch-all connect.CodeInternal branch.

This means calling CheckViolation before a constitution has been bootstrapped returns HTTP 500 (Internal) instead of a meaningful client error such as CodeFailedPrecondition (412) or CodeNotFound (404).

Suggested fix: add an ErrConstitutionNotFound check in the handler before the fallthrough:

  if errors.Is(err, storage.ErrConstitutionNotFound) {
      return nil, connect.NewError(connect.CodeFailedPrecondition, fmt.Errorf("no constitution has been configured"))
  }

This matches the existing pattern used in GetConstitution and EmitToolFiles.

