File: internal/storage/memgraph/memgraph.go, recordString function (line ~6786)

    func recordString(rec *neo4j.Record, i int) string {
        v, ok := rec.Values[i].(string)
        if !ok {
            return ""
        }
        return v
    }

When a record value cannot be type-asserted to string (e.g., the database returned nil, an integer, or an unexpected type), the function silently returns an empty string. This affects all callers: recordToClaim, recordToDecision, recordToSpec, and the graph query helpers. The result is that corrupted or unexpected data is silently normalized to an empty field, making the returned struct appear valid. For fields like ID, slug, or agent, an empty string is a data error that should fail loudly.

Likewise recordInt64 silently returns 0 on type mismatch (line ~6795). A version field defaulting to 0 when the DB returns something unexpected would cause silent version counter corruption.

Suggested fix: Return (string, bool) or (string, error) from these helpers, or at minimum log a warning and surface an error to the caller when an unexpected type is encountered at a position that must be non-empty (e.g., ID, slug).

