File: internal/storage/memgraph/memgraph.go

The comment above generateID reads:
  // generateID produces a prefixed ID from sha256(slug + now).
  // The result is prefix + "-" + hex chars, truncated to targetLen.

The function signature is:
  func generateID(prefix, slug string, now time.Time) string

There is no 'targetLen' parameter. The truncation logic uses a hardcoded expression (len(prefix)+8), not any variable called targetLen. The comment is factually wrong and will mislead anyone trying to understand or modify the ID generation logic.

Suggested fix: Replace the second comment line with:
  // The result is prefix + "-" + hex chars, total length capped at len(prefix)+9.

In /internal/storage/memgraph/memgraph.go:generateID (line 6763-6769):

  func generateID(prefix, slug string, now time.Time) string {
      h := sha256.Sum256([]byte(slug + now.String()))
      id := fmt.Sprintf("%s-%x", prefix, h[:4])
      if len(id) > len(prefix)+8 {
          id = id[:len(prefix)+8]
      }
      return id
  }

h[:4] encodes to 8 hex characters, so the full id is len(prefix)+1+8 characters (prefix, dash, 8 hex chars). The guard condition checks len(id) > len(prefix)+8, which is true only when the id is longer than prefix+8 chars. Since the dash already adds 1 character, len(id) == len(prefix)+9 always, so the truncation fires on every call and trims the last character of the hex digest, yielding only 7 hex chars.

The original code (before refactor) produced 7 hex chars by design (see comment: 'spec-' (5) + 7 hex chars = 12), so the logic is preserved accidentally. However, for non-'spec' prefixes like 'dec' (3 chars), the guard produces len('dec')+8 = 11 chars limit, but the id is 3+1+8 = 12 chars, so truncation again cuts to 11 (7 hex chars, same as before). The intent and the comment are at odds with the guard condition — the condition should read > len(prefix)+1+8 to avoid truncation, or the truncation limit should be len(prefix)+1+7.

This causes shorter IDs than documented and could reduce uniqueness guarantees. Fix: decide on the target length and make the condition explicit:
  const hexLen = 8
  id := fmt.Sprintf("%s-%x", prefix, h[:hexLen/2])
  // id is always len(prefix)+1+hexLen chars, no truncation needed

File: cmd/specgraph/init.go, readLine function (lines 700-706)

    func readLine(r *bufio.Reader) string {
        line, err := r.ReadString('\n')
        if err != nil {
            return strings.TrimSpace(line) // return partial on EOF
        }
        return strings.TrimSpace(line)
    }

The comment says 'return partial on EOF' but the function also swallows any other io.Reader errors (e.g., broken pipe, device error) without distinguishing them from EOF. A broken-pipe or read error mid-input will return the partial content as if it were the user's intentional answer. This can silently accept an empty or partial backend/mode value, which then propagates into the written config file.

Suggested fix: Return (string, error) from readLine and handle non-EOF errors explicitly in runInit. Alternatively, check errors.Is(err, io.EOF) and return an error for any other read failure.

