The refactored generateID in internal/storage/memgraph/memgraph.go has a subtle bug and needless complexity:

func generateID(prefix, slug string, now time.Time) string {
    h := sha256.Sum256([]byte(slug + now.String()))
    id := fmt.Sprintf("%s-%x", prefix, h[:4])
    if len(id) > len(prefix)+8 {
        id = id[:len(prefix)+8]
    }
    return id
}

Issues:
1. h[:4] encodes to 8 hex chars. The full id is len(prefix)+1+8 characters. The condition len(id) > len(prefix)+8 is always true (there is always a "-" separator), so the branch always truncates — by exactly one character, chopping a hex digit every time. For prefix="spec" that gives "spec-" (5) + 7 chars = 12, matching the old code, but for prefix="dec" it gives "dec-" (4) + 7 chars = 11, not the 12 characters the old code produced.
2. The conditional truncation can be replaced with a direct slice of the hash: encode exactly 3.5 bytes if 7 hex chars are wanted, or decide on a consistent length.

Suggested fix — pick an explicit hex length and encode it directly:
const idHexLen = 7  // 7 hex chars from 4 bytes (last nibble dropped)

func generateID(prefix, slug string, now time.Time) string {
    h := sha256.Sum256([]byte(slug + now.String()))
    return fmt.Sprintf("%s-%x", prefix, h[:4])[:len(prefix)+1+idHexLen]
}

Or encode only 3.5 bytes cleanly by using h[:4] and slicing the formatted string to a fixed total length determined by the caller. Either way the conditional should be removed in favour of a predictable, documented output length.

Both internal/storage/memgraph/memgraph.go UpdateSpec and internal/storage/memgraph/decision.go UpdateDecision use the identical pattern for building dynamic Cypher SET clauses from optional pointer fields: declare a setClauses slice and params map, range over the optional fields appending to both, guard on empty result, then append the updated_at clause and run fmt.Sprintf to build the query.

This pattern is duplicated verbatim (~20 lines each). A small helper such as:
type setBuilder struct { clauses []string; params map[string]any }
func (b *setBuilder) add(clause, key string, val any) { ... }

would eliminate the repetition and make both update functions a handful of lines each. This is lower priority since the pattern is not yet used in a third place, but noting it before a third update method arrives.

In /internal/server/claim_handler.go:UnclaimSpec (line 4657) and /internal/storage/memgraph/claim.go:UnclaimSpec (line 5848), the implementation uses a Cypher DELETE that silently does nothing if the (slug, agent) combination doesn't match. A different agent could call UnclaimSpec with any slug and get a 200 OK even though no claim existed or the agent didn't own it.

This is a functional authorization gap: any agent can 'release' any spec claim with no error and no record of the attempt.

