In internal/authoring/safety.go lines 818-836, RunSafetyNet contains two nearly identical loops — one for securityPatterns and one for dataLossPatterns. Both iterate a []string, call strings.Contains on the combined text, and append a SafetyFlagResult with the same Severity. The only differences are the category string and the pattern slice.

The duplication could be eliminated with a local helper:

  type patternGroup struct {
      category string
      patterns []string
  }

  groups := []patternGroup{
      {SafetyCategorySecurity, securityPatterns},
      {SafetyCategoryDataLoss, dataLossPatterns},
  }
  for _, g := range groups {
      for _, p := range g.patterns {
          if strings.Contains(combined, p) {
              flags = append(flags, SafetyFlagResult{
                  Category:    g.category,
                  Severity:    specv1.FindingSeverity_FINDING_SEVERITY_CRITICAL,
                  Description: "matched pattern: " + p,
              })
          }
      }
  }

This halves the loop body and makes adding a third category (e.g. privacy) a one-liner.

In internal/authoring/stages.go lines 958-983, ValidateTransition first checks the forwardTransitions map (fast path), then falls through to indexOf for backward transitions. However, the forward map and the stages slice are maintained as two separate data structures that must stay in sync. The map lookup at line 964 actually makes the indexOf calls at lines 969-970 redundant for valid forward transitions — but indexOf is still called unconditionally after the map check fails.

More importantly, the forward map is derivable from the stages slice at init time, which means there are now two sources of truth for ordering. A simpler approach keeps only the slice and derives forward transitions from it:

  func ValidateTransition(from, to string) error {
      if from == to {
          return fmt.Errorf("transition from %q to %q is a no-op", from, to)
      }
      fromIdx := indexOf(from)
      toIdx   := indexOf(to)
      if from != "" && fromIdx < 0 {
          return fmt.Errorf("unknown stage %q", from)
      }
      if toIdx < 0 {
          return fmt.Errorf("unknown stage %q", to)
      }
      // forward: must be exactly the next stage
      if from == "" && toIdx == 0 {
          return nil
      }
      if fromIdx >= 0 && toIdx == fromIdx+1 {
          return nil
      }
      // backward: any earlier stage
      if fromIdx >= 0 && toIdx < fromIdx {
          return nil
      }
      return fmt.Errorf("invalid transition from %q to %q", from, to)
  }

This removes forwardTransitions entirely, eliminating the dual-maintenance burden.

File: internal/server/authoring_handler.go

Only the Spark handler validates that the slug is non-empty (line 30-32). The Shape, Specify, Decompose, Approve, Amend, and Supersede handlers pass req.Msg.Slug directly to storage without validation. An empty slug (or malformed slug) reaches the Memgraph query layer, producing internal storage error messages that are wrapped and returned to the caller via connect.NewError(connect.CodeInternal, err).

While not immediately exploitable, this creates two issues:
1. Internal error messages from storage may leak implementation details to callers (error detail in CodeInternal responses).
2. Inconsistent validation behavior: Spark returns CodeInvalidArgument for empty slug, but other endpoints return CodeNotFound or CodeFailedPrecondition depending on how Memgraph handles the empty match.

Recommended fix: Add a shared validateSlug helper and call it at the top of each handler:

  func validateSlug(slug string) error {
      if slug == "" {
          return connect.NewError(connect.CodeInvalidArgument, errors.New("slug is required"))
      }
      return nil
  }

Apply to all 7 RPCs that accept a slug field.

